In this exercise you will create some simulated data and will fit simple linear regression models to it. Make sure to use set.seed(1) prior to starting part (a) to ensure consistent results.rnorm

  1. Using the rnorm() function, create a vector, “x”, containing 100 observations drawn from a N(0,1) distribution. This represents a feature, X.
set.seed(1)
x=rnorm(100,mean = 0,sd=1)
  1. Using the rnorm() function, create a vector, “eps”, containing 100 observations drawn from a N(0,0.25) distribution.
eps=rnorm(100,0,sqrt(0.25))
  1. Using “x” and “eps”, generate a vector “y” according to the model Y=−1+0.5X+ε. What is the length of the vector “y” ? What are the values of β0 and β1 in this linear model ?
y =-1+0.5*x+eps
length(y)
## [1] 100

The length of the vector “y”= 100. The values of β0=-1, β1=0.

  1. Create a scatterplot displaying the relationship between “x” and “y”. Comment on what you observe.
plot(x,y)

The relationship between “x” and “y” looks linear.

  1. Fit a least squares linear model to predict “y” using “x”. Comment on the model obtained. How do β^0 and β^1 compare to β0 and β1 ?
Fit=lm(y~x)
